```python import requests import datetime import markdown
# Define the domains for categorization domains = { "Healthcare": [], "Finance": [], "Education": [], "Technology": [], "Others": [] }
# Get the date one week ago one_week_ago = datetime.datetime.now() - datetime.timedelta(days=7)
# Construct the ArXiv API query url = f"http://export.arxiv.org/api/query?search_query=all:large+language+models&start=0&max_results=100&sortBy=submittedDate&sortOrder=descending"
# Make the request to the ArXiv API response = requests.get(url) data = response.text
# Parse the data import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET root = ET.fromstring(data)
# Extract relevant information for entry in root.findall('{http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom}entry'): title = entry.find('{http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom}title').text author = entry.find('{http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom}author').find('{http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom}name').text published = entry.find('{http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom}published').text summary = entry.find('{http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom}summary').text url = entry.find('{http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom}id').text
# Convert published date from string to datetime published_date = datetime.datetime.fromisoformat(published[:-1])
# Check if the paper was published in the last week if published_date >= one_week_ago: # Categorize based on keywords in the summary if "health" in summary.lower(): domains["Healthcare"].append((title, author, published, url)) elif "finance" in summary.lower(): domains["Finance"].append((title, author, published, url)) elif "education" in summary.lower(): domains["Education"].append((title, author, published, url)) elif "technology" in summary.lower(): domains["Technology"].append((title, author, published, url)) else: domains["Others"].append((title, author, published, url))
# Prepare the markdown table markdown_output = "| Domain | Title | Authors | Published | URL ||--------------|-------|---------|-----------|-----|" for domain, papers in domains.items(): for paper in papers: title, author, published, url = paper markdown_output += f"| {domain} | {title} | {author} | {published} | {url} |"
# Write the markdown output to a file with open("LLM_Applications.md", "w") as f: f.write(markdown_output)
print("Markdown table created successfully.") ``` This script queries the ArXiv API for recent papers related to large language models, categorizes them into different domains based on their summaries, and generates a markdown table with relevant details. The generated markdown table will be saved in the file `LLM_Applications.md`.
